{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6805e78c-3e23-49f3-919e-edd2c4f708d4","content":"The repository is empty, so I'll answer from general knowledge.\n\nOn macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes without `createdump`, you can recover a crash dump via the **OS-level core dump mechanism**:\n\n1. **Enable core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS stores them under `/cores/`):\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/cores/core.%P\n   ```\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash.** A `core.<pid>` file should appear in `/cores/`.\n\n4. **If `/cores/` is empty**, check that:\n   - SIP (System Integrity Protection) isn't blocking it.\n   - The binary is **not** code-signed with the `restrict` entitlement. Strip or re-sign if needed:\n     ```bash\n     codesign --remove-signature ./myapp\n     ```\n\n5. **Check Apple's crash logs** as a fallback — macOS writes `.ips` crash reports to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These contain stack traces and register state (not full memory dumps, but often sufficient for triage).\n\n6. **Analyze the core file** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb ./myapp -c /cores/core.12345\n   ```\n\n**Key caveat for NativeAOT:** Since there's no managed runtime, `dotnet-dump` won't work. Use `lldb` with SOS or the native debugging workflow. If you built with debug symbols (`-p:StripSymbols=false`), `lldb` will resolve managed method names.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d83c78d6-1432-45ac-ab3d-b7d72a997051","outputTokens":403,"requestId":"943F:11496B:27C622:2F0AA7:69E82066"},"id":"e927b135-d2e9-4f02-bcaf-d39353cbe72b","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:12:17.281Z","parentId":"0cf488a2-2343-4da3-b646-3178fba5e167"}
